	<section id="swap_content" align="TOP|LEFT" spacing="0" autospace="false" columns="0" exclusive="true" expanded="true">
		<container id="swap_content01" behavior="LOCK_SIZE" x="340" y="140" visible="false" fx="SWAP_SHOW" hidefx="SWAP_HIDE" style="">
			<text id="header" x="0" y="0" width="350" height="" autosize="H" style="DEFAULT" visible="true" fx="">
				<content translate="true">&lt;B&gt;Early Communication (0–18 months)&lt;/B&gt;</content>
			</text>
			<text id="text" x="0" y="25" width="424" height="" autosize="H" style="DEFAULT" visible="true" fx="">
				<content translate="true">&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;The first phase explores how babies' communication skills emerge during the first year of life. Even the youngest babies are eager to engage with the people around them by cooing, babbling, pointing, and eventually forming their first words.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;During the early communication phase parents should try to recognize cues and engage in social referencing.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;LI&gt;&lt;/LI&gt;&lt;TEXTFORMAT BLOCKINDENT="16"&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;B&gt;Cues:&lt;/B&gt; Signals that babies give such as crying, rooting, &lt;/P&gt;&lt;/TEXTFORMAT&gt;&lt;TEXTFORMAT BLOCKINDENT="16"&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;and smiling&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/TEXTFORMAT&gt;&lt;TEXTFORMAT BLOCKINDENT="16"&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/TEXTFORMAT&gt;&lt;TEXTFORMAT BLOCKINDENT="16"&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;B&gt;Social referencing:&lt;/B&gt; Looking to an adult for affirmation or redirection of an intended action&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/TEXTFORMAT&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;/P&gt;</content>
			</text>
		</container>
		<container id="swap_content02" behavior="LOCK_SIZE" x="" y="155" visible="false" fx="SWAP_SHOW" hidefx="SWAP_HIDE" style="">
			<text id="header" x="0" y="0" width="350" height="" autosize="H" style="DEFAULT" visible="true" fx="">
				<content translate="true">&lt;B&gt;Verbal Development (18–36 months)&lt;/B&gt;</content>
			</text>
			<text id="text" x="0" y="25" width="414" height="" autosize="H" style="DEFAULT" visible="true" fx="">
				<content translate="true">&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;The second phase examines language acquisition and how toddlers learn new words as their vocabularies expand. During the second phase, the focus is on toddlers learning to imitate, express needs, and discover meaning.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;TEXTFORMAT BLOCKINDENT="16"&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;B&gt;Imitate: &lt;/B&gt;Verbal skills increase as toddlers imitate sounds and eventually the words they hear spoken to them.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/TEXTFORMAT&gt;&lt;TEXTFORMAT BLOCKINDENT="16"&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/TEXTFORMAT&gt;&lt;TEXTFORMAT BLOCKINDENT="16"&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;B&gt;Express needs:&lt;/B&gt; Developing language allows toddlers to better express their needs. This new ability to communicate needs reduces frustration and temper tantrums.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/TEXTFORMAT&gt;&lt;TEXTFORMAT BLOCKINDENT="16"&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/TEXTFORMAT&gt;&lt;TEXTFORMAT BLOCKINDENT="16"&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;B&gt;Discover meaning: &lt;/B&gt;Toddlers begin to quickly match the words they hear to the meaning of the word. They move past only imitating words to using words intentionally to communicate.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/TEXTFORMAT&gt;</content>
			</text>
		</container>
		<container id="swap_content03" behavior="LOCK_SIZE" x="" y="190" visible="false" fx="SWAP_SHOW" hidefx="SWAP_HIDE" style="">
			<text id="header" x="0" y="0" width="350" height="" autosize="H" style="DEFAULT" visible="true" fx="">
				<content translate="true">&lt;B&gt;Emergent Literacy (3–5 years)&lt;/B&gt;</content>
			</text>
			<text id="text" x="0" y="25" width="395" height="" autosize="H" style="DEFAULT" visible="true" fx="">
				<content translate="true">&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;This final phase of early childhood language development takes a look at how preschoolers and kindergarteners become more sophisticated in their ability to communicate.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;TEXTFORMAT BLOCKINDENT="16"&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;B&gt;Preschoolers: &lt;/B&gt;Three- and four-year-olds learn to use language in a social context. They start having more of a back-and-forth dialogue and start building independence in their language by wanting to express their own thoughts.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/TEXTFORMAT&gt;&lt;TEXTFORMAT BLOCKINDENT="16"&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/TEXTFORMAT&gt;&lt;TEXTFORMAT BLOCKINDENT="16"&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;B&gt;Kindergarteners:&lt;/B&gt; Language skills for 5-year-olds focus more on the formal educational aspects of language. For example, children engage more in word play, such as rhyming games. They also focus more on emerging written communication skills including pre-reading and writing.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/TEXTFORMAT&gt;</content>
			</text>
		</container>
